06555nam a22008295i 9783110376616DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20152015gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)940512206  a97831103766167 a10.1515/97831103766162doi  a(DE-B1597)429644  a(OCoLC)925482023  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aJC571 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a32300aImagining Human Rights /ced. by Susanne Kaul, David Kim. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (227 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tTable Of Contents -- tIntroduction: Imagining Human Rights -- tThe Sacredness of the Person or The Last Utopia: A Conversation about the History of Human Rights -- tSection One: Claiming Human Rights -- tThe Progressive Potential of Human Rights -- tThe More Who Die, the Less We Care Psychic Numbing and Genocide -- tOn Invoking Human Rights When There Aren't Any -- tThe Cosmopolitics of Parrhesia: Foucault and Truth-Telling as Human Right -- tImagining Threatened Peoples: The Society for Threatened Peoples (Gesellschaft für bedrohte Völker) in 1970s West Germany -- tNeoliberal Charity: German Contraband Humanitarians in Kenya -- tSection Two: Human Rights In Imagination -- tPoetic Anarchy and Human Rights: Dissensus in Georg Büchner's Danton's Death and Peter Weiss's Marat/Sade -- tThe Aesthetics of Human Rights in Franz Werfel's The Forty Days of Musa Dagh -- tThe Right To Tell That It Hurt: Fiction and Political Performance of Human Rights in South Africa -- tEmbodiment and Immigrant Rights in Alejandro González Iñárritu's Biutiful -- tWhy Them and Not I? An Account of Kalliopi Lemos's Art Projects About Human Dignity -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Persons -- tIndex of Subjects0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWhy is it that human rights are considered inviolable norms of justice at local and global scales although the number of their violations has steadily increased in modern history? On the surface, this paradox seems to be reducible to a straightforward discrepancy between idealism and reality in humanitarian affairs, but Imagining Human Rights complicates the picture by offering interdisciplinary perspectives on the imaginary status of human rights. By that the contributors mean not merely subject to imagination, open to interpretation or far too abstract, but also formative of a social imaginary with emphatic identifications and shared values. From a variety of disciplinary perspectives, they explore critical ways of engaging in rigorous interdisciplinary conversations about the origin and language of human rights, personal dignity, redistributive justice, and international solidarity. Together, they show how and why a careful examination of the intersection between disciplinary investigations is essential for imagining human rights at large. Examples range from the legitimacy of land ownership rights and the inadequacy of human faculty to make sense of mass violence in visual representation to the stewardship of human rights promoters and the genealogy of human rights.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aHuman rights. 4aGerechtigkeit. 4aLiteratur. 4aRecht. 4aWürde. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aliterature, dignity, justice, law.1 aBerman, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBittner, Rüdiger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBösch, Michael, e